declare(strict_types=1);
echo '<div class="mk-prose">';
echo '<p class="mk-muted" style="margin-top:0;">Ancient and classical religions at thesis level — beliefs, doctrines, proselytism, apostasy, birth, marriage, death, and the afterlife for each tradition.</p>';
echo '<p>Ancient religions present a unique challenge: most are extinct, known primarily through archaeological evidence, inscriptions, and the accounts of outsiders (often hostile ones). We document what the evidence allows while acknowledging its limits. Where ancient sources are ambiguous or contradictory, we say so.</p>';

// KEMET
echo '<hr style="margin:28px 0;border:none;border-top:2px solid #e5e7eb;">';
echo '<h2 style="color:#b7791f;">⊕ Kemet (Ancient Egyptian Religion) — Full Doctrinal Treatment</h2>';
echo '<p><strong>Theism:</strong> Functionally polytheistic; esoterically monotheistic (Amun as the hidden unity) | <strong>Period:</strong> c. 3100 BCE – 400 CE | <strong>Status:</strong> Extinct; revived as Kemetism</p>';

echo '<h3>Faith and Belief</h3>';
echo '<p>Ancient Egyptian religion was not a system of faith in the Abrahamic sense — it did not require intellectual assent to propositions. It was a system of relationship maintenance: maintaining the proper relationships between humans, gods, pharaoh, and the cosmic order (Ma\'at). The Egyptian equivalent of "faith" was perhaps <em>meryt</em> (love/devotion toward the gods) and <em>shefyt</em> (awe/respect for divine power). One demonstrated one\'s right relationship with the divine through ritual, ethical conduct, and the maintenance of cosmic order.</p>';
echo '<p>The theological sophistication of Egyptian religion operated on multiple levels simultaneously. The popular level: a rich pantheon of anthropomorphic and theriomorphic deities with complex mythological relationships. The priestly level: careful management of temple ritual as cosmic maintenance. The esoteric level: the recognition that all gods are aspects of the one hidden divine reality — expressed most explicitly in the Leiden Hymn to Amun: "All gods are three: Amun, Re, and Ptah, whom none equals. He who hides his name as Amun, he appears to the face as Re, his body is Ptah."</p>';

echo '<h3>Doctrines</h3>';
echo '<ul>';
echo '<li><strong>Ma\'at</strong> — the central doctrine; cosmic order, truth, justice, and balance. The universe exists through Ma\'at; its disruption is isefet (chaos, evil). Pharaoh\'s primary function was to maintain Ma\'at — offering Ma\'at to the gods and implementing it in society through just rule.</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Divine Kingship</strong> — Pharaoh was the living Horus (god of divine kingship) and the dead Osiris (after death). This made Pharaoh the sole legitimate intermediary between humans and gods — a doctrine that justified the entire pyramid of Egyptian political and religious power.</li>';
echo '<li><strong>The Multiple Souls</strong> — Egyptians understood the human being as comprising multiple soul-components: Ka (life force/double), Ba (personality/spirit that travels), Akh (the transfigured spiritual being after successful afterlife transformation), Ib (heart as moral center), Ren (name — speaking the name keeps the person alive), Sheut (shadow). The afterlife was the process of integrating and transfiguring these components into the Akh.</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Creation</strong> — multiple creation accounts coexisted without contradiction: the Heliopolitan account (Atum created himself from Nun, the primordial waters, then produced the other gods); the Memphite account (Ptah created through thought and speech — the Logos doctrine); the Hermopolitan account (eight primordial beings created through the interplay of primordial qualities). Egyptians did not require cosmological consistency — different temples maintained different cosmologies, all understood as true at different levels.</li>';
echo '</ul>';

echo '<h3>Proselytism</h3>';
echo '<p>Ancient Egyptian religion did not proselytize. It was the religion of Egypt — embedded in the land, the Nile, the pharaonic institution, and the temple system. Non-Egyptians who settled in Egypt typically adopted Egyptian religious practice as part of cultural integration, but there was no systematic effort to convert foreigners. The cult of Isis was the exception: as Egypt was absorbed into the Roman world, Isiac religion spread throughout the Mediterranean as the most widely adopted Egyptian tradition, eventually reaching Britain. This was not missionary activity but the natural diffusion of a compelling tradition through trade, travel, and cultural contact.</p>';

echo '<h3>Apostasy</h3>';
echo '<p>The concept of apostasy is anachronistic for ancient Egyptian religion — there was no defined membership to abandon. However, the closest equivalent was the rejection of Ma\'at: denying the gods, failing to perform required rituals, or transgressing moral norms that were understood as cosmically maintained. Such transgressions were not merely social offenses but cosmic ones — disrupting the balance that kept the world in order. The most dramatic historical "apostasy" was Akhenaten\'s (c. 1353–1336 BCE) attempted monotheistic revolution: his worship of the Aten (sun disc) as the sole god, the closure of other temples, and the erasure of gods\' names (especially Amun). After his death, his reforms were reversed, his monuments defaced, and his name expunged from records — the pharaonic version of damnatio memoriae.</p>';

echo '<h3>Birth Traditions</h3>';
echo '<ul>';
echo '<li><strong>Protection of mother and child</strong> — elaborate magical and ritual protections surrounded pregnancy and birth; amulets of Taweret (the hippopotamus goddess of pregnancy) and Bes (the dwarf god protecting mother and child) were kept in birthing rooms</li>';
echo '<li><strong>The birth brick</strong> — women gave birth squatting on two birth bricks; these bricks were sacred objects symbolizing the moment of transition from non-existence to life</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Naming</strong> — the child\'s name (ren) was essential to its identity and survival; the ren was the soul-component that kept the person alive; knowing someone\'s true name gave power over them; names were chosen carefully for their meaning and divine associations</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Circumcision</strong> — practiced in ancient Egypt; Egyptian circumcision predates the biblical institution and may have influenced it; documented in tomb reliefs</li>';
echo '</ul>';

echo '<h3>Marriage Traditions</h3>';
echo '<p>Ancient Egyptian marriage was primarily a legal and social contract, not a religious ceremony. There was no wedding ritual equivalent to the Christian or Hindu sacrament of marriage. A couple became married by establishing a household together — a practical arrangement typically involving property agreements. Egyptian women had significant legal rights: they could own property, initiate divorce, and appear in court. Marriage was monogamous for most Egyptians, though pharaohs and high officials maintained multiple wives. Love poetry from ancient Egypt — preserved on papyri and ostraca — reveals a culture with a rich vocabulary of romantic devotion. The gods did not perform or sanction marriages; the family, the community, and the law governed matrimonial arrangements.</p>';

echo '<h3>Death and the Afterlife</h3>';
echo '<p>Egyptian afterlife theology is the most elaborate and extensively documented of any ancient civilization. Death was not an ending but a transformation — the most difficult journey of one\'s existence, requiring ritual preparation, moral integrity, and magical assistance:</p>';
echo '<ul>';
echo '<li><strong>Mummification</strong> — the body was preserved to maintain a physical anchor for the Ba and Ka; the process took 70 days; internal organs (except the heart) were removed and preserved in canopic jars; the heart remained because it would be weighed at judgment</li>';
echo '<li><strong>The Hall of Two Truths (Weighing of the Heart)</strong> — the most dramatic moment of the Egyptian afterlife: the deceased\'s heart was weighed against the feather of Ma\'at on a scale; Thoth recorded the result; Anubis supervised the weighing; 42 assessor-gods witnessed the negative confession (the deceased denied committing specific sins); if the heart was lighter than the feather, the deceased passed; if heavier, the heart was devoured by Ammit (part lion, part hippopotamus, part crocodile) and the person ceased to exist</li>';
echo '<li><strong>The negative confession (Spell 125 of the Book of the Dead)</strong> — 42 declarations of moral innocence: "I have not stolen. I have not killed. I have not lied. I have not committed adultery. I have not spoken evil of the king..." — a remarkable document of Egyptian ethics</li>';
echo '<li><strong>The Field of Reeds (Aaru)</strong> — paradise; an idealized version of Egypt where the righteous lived in abundance, farming rich land beside canals, reunited with loved ones</li>';
echo '<li><strong>The Duat (Underworld)</strong> — the region through which the deceased traveled; the Book of the Dead, the Amduat, and other funerary texts provided maps and spells to navigate its dangers</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Tomb provisions</strong> — food, furniture, clothing, tools, and shabti figurines (servants) were buried with the dead to supply their afterlife needs; the quality and quantity of tomb goods reflected the deceased\'s earthly wealth and status</li>';
echo '</ul>';

echo '<h3>Metempsychosis</h3>';
echo '<p>Mainstream ancient Egyptian theology did not teach reincarnation back into human bodies in the Hindu sense. However, the Ba could return to the tomb and to the physical world; the soul had a complex existence that involved movement between different realms. Some scholars argue that certain Egyptian texts imply cyclical return, particularly the solar imagery of death and rebirth repeated daily. The concept of the soul passing through many forms after death — perhaps through animal bodies — appears in some later Demotic papyri, possibly influenced by Pythagorean or Platonic ideas.</p>';

// MESOPOTAMIAN
echo '<hr style="margin:28px 0;border:none;border-top:2px solid #e5e7eb;">';
echo '<h2 style="color:#276749;">⊕ Mesopotamian Religion — Full Doctrinal Treatment</h2>';
echo '<p><strong>Theism:</strong> Polytheistic | <strong>Period:</strong> c. 3500 – 539 BCE | <strong>Status:</strong> Extinct</p>';

echo '<h3>Faith and Belief</h3>';
echo '<p>Mesopotamian religion — the religious systems of the Sumerians, Akkadians, Babylonians, and Assyrians — was a religion of cosmic service. Humans were created to serve the gods: to feed them through sacrifice, to house them in temples, to clothe them, to sing their praises, and to perform the labor that maintained civilization. This was not understood as degrading — it was the purpose for which humans were made, as stated explicitly in the Atrahasis myth and the Enuma Elish. The gods needed human service; humans needed divine favor. The relationship was one of mutual dependence, not master and slave.</p>';
echo '<p>Mesopotamian faith was empirical in its own way: if you performed the correct rituals with the correct intentions and the gods still did not respond, the appropriate conclusion was not that the gods did not exist but that something had gone wrong — perhaps an offense had been committed that required specific expiation, or a demon had intervened, or the diviner had misread the omens. The elaborate Babylonian omen literature (thousands of clay tablets cataloguing omens and their interpretations) represents a systematic attempt to understand the communication between the divine and human worlds.</p>';

echo '<h3>Doctrines</h3>';
echo '<ul>';
echo '<li><strong>The divine assembly (Anunnaki)</strong> — the major gods formed an assembly that made cosmic decisions by vote and debate; Enlil presided; decisions were communicated through the Tablets of Destiny; the cosmos was governed by divine consensus, not divine autocracy</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Me (divine laws/powers)</strong> — the divine principles or powers that organized civilization: kingship, priesthood, the descent to the underworld, truth, the scribal arts, music, the stability of cities. These Me were possessed by Enki/Ea and could be stolen, transferred, or lost — a cosmic anxiety expressed in the myth of Inanna\'s descent and the poem of Gilgamesh</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Personal god</strong> — every individual had a personal deity (a lesser god assigned to them from birth) who interceded with the major gods on their behalf. If one\'s personal god abandoned them (through offense or cosmic mischance), misfortune followed. Restoring the personal god\'s favor was the goal of many rituals and lamentations.</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Fate (Namtar)</strong> — destinies were decreed by the assembly of gods and written on the Tablets of Fate; divination was the technology for discovering one\'s fate; some fates could be altered through prayer and ritual.</li>';
echo '</ul>';

echo '<h3>Birth, Marriage, and Death</h3>';
echo '<ul>';
echo '<li><strong>Birth</strong> — midwives performed rituals to protect mother and child; amulets against Lamashtu (the demon who killed infants) were worn; the goddess Ninhursag was the divine midwife; naming occurred at birth with reference to divine favor ("Enlil-bani" — Enlil is my creator)</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Marriage</strong> — a legal contract between families; dowry and bride-price were specified in written agreements; marriage was monogamous in practice for most; divorce was permitted for both parties under certain conditions; the sacred marriage (Hieros Gamos) between the king and the high priestess of Inanna was a state ritual ensuring divine fertility and royal legitimacy</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Death</strong> — the dead descended to Kur or Irkalla (the underworld) — a dark, dusty realm beneath the earth where all the dead lived regardless of their virtue; the queen of the underworld was Ereshkigal; the dead ate dust and clay unless provided for by the living; regular offerings of food and water by descendants were essential to the dead\'s wellbeing; the dead who were not properly buried or provided for became restless spirits (etemmu) who could afflict the living</li>';
echo '<li><strong>No resurrection or paradise</strong> — uniquely among ancient Near Eastern religions, Mesopotamian religion offered no hope of paradise or resurrection for ordinary people; kings might join the gods, but commoners simply existed as diminished shades in the underworld forever; this grim eschatology drove the pessimistic wisdom of Ecclesiastes-style literature and the Gilgamesh epic\'s meditation on mortality</li>';
echo '</ul>';

echo '<h3>Proselytism and Apostasy</h3>';
echo '<p>Mesopotamian religion did not proselytize — it was the religion of specific city-states and their patron deities. When Babylon conquered other cities, they typically imposed Marduk\'s supremacy but did not systematically suppress local cults. When peoples were conquered and deported (as the Assyrians did extensively), they maintained their own religious practices. There was no concept of apostasy — one could add new gods to one\'s devotion or emphasize different ones without being considered unfaithful to any of them.</p>';

// NORSE
echo '<hr style="margin:28px 0;border:none;border-top:2px solid #e5e7eb;">';
echo '<h2 style="color:#2d3748;">⊕ Norse Religion — Full Doctrinal Treatment</h2>';
echo '<p><strong>Theism:</strong> Polytheistic | <strong>Period:</strong> c. 200 – 1100 CE | <strong>Status:</strong> Extinct; revived as Ásatrú/Heathenry</p>';

echo '<h3>Faith and Belief</h3>';
echo '<p>Norse religion — the religious system of the pre-Christian Germanic and Scandinavian peoples — was a religion without dogma in any formal sense. There were no councils, no creeds, no orthodoxy to enforce. What held the tradition together was not shared belief but shared practice (ritual, sacrifice, seasonal festival) and shared story (the mythological corpus preserved in the Eddas). The Norse equivalent of faith was perhaps <em>trúa</em> (trust/belief) — a trust in the gods\' power and goodwill based on the reciprocal relationship maintained through sacrifice and prayer. But this was trust built on experience and obligation, not on revealed doctrine.</p>';
echo '<p>The Norse religious attitude was intensely pragmatic: the gods were real, powerful beings with their own interests, limitations, and destinies. They deserved honor and sacrifice because they protected and aided humans — and because the relationship was maintained across generations by one\'s ancestors. If a god failed to deliver results despite proper sacrifice, a worshipper might complain directly (as documented in some saga accounts) or switch allegiance. The gods were partners, not absolute sovereigns.</p>';

echo '<h3>Doctrines</h3>';
echo '<ul>';
echo '<li><strong>Wyrd (Fate)</strong> — the inescapable web of fate woven by the Norns (Urð, Verðandi, Skuld — past, present, becoming). Wyrd applied to gods and humans alike — even Odin knew that he would die at Ragnarök. The Norse response to inescapable fate was not resignation but heroic engagement: one should face one\'s fate with courage, skill, and honor. The manner of meeting one\'s fate mattered enormously even if the outcome was predetermined.</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Frith</strong> — peace, social harmony, the bonds of kinship and community. The central social value; violation of frith (through murder of a kinsman, betrayal of a host, oath-breaking) was the gravest social transgression and carried spiritual consequences.</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Honor (drengskapr)</strong> — the Norse value system centered on honor: courage in battle, generosity with followers, skill in craft and poetry, faithfulness to oaths. These were not merely social virtues but spiritually significant qualities that determined one\'s fate after death.</li>';
echo '<li><strong>The Nine Worlds</strong> — a cosmological structure connecting all levels of reality through the world tree Yggdrasil; acknowledging and respecting the beings of all nine worlds was part of religious practice</li>';
echo '</ul>';

echo '<h3>Proselytism and Apostasy</h3>';
echo '<p>Norse religion did not proselytize. It was the ancestral tradition of specific peoples, transmitted through family and community practice. Conversion to Christianity was typically forced — imposed by kings through military power (Olaf Tryggvason of Norway famously tortured or killed those who refused conversion). The "apostasy" of Christianization was experienced as a civilizational rupture rather than individual religious choice: an entire people\'s ancestral relationships with their gods were severed by royal decree. Those who maintained the old practices (the seiðr practitioners, the holders of blót tradition) became increasingly marginalized, persecuted, and eventually extinct in Europe, surviving only in Iceland in attenuated form.</p>';

echo '<h3>Birth Traditions</h3>';
echo '<ul>';
echo '<li><strong>Naming ceremony</strong> — the father formally recognized the child by laying it on his knee (barn á kné) and giving it a name; until this occurred, the child could be exposed without it being considered murder; the naming bound the child to the family and its ancestral wyrd</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Water sprinkling (ausa vatni)</strong> — water was poured over the infant while the name was spoken; this predated Christian baptism in Scandinavia and was absorbed into Christian practice as a parallel</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Names and fate</strong> — naming a child after a dead ancestor was believed to bring the ancestor\'s luck and qualities into the new life; a form of ancestral reincarnation through naming</li>';
echo '</ul>';

echo '<h3>Marriage Traditions</h3>';
echo '<ul>';
echo '<li><strong>Handfasting</strong> — the joining of hands (Old Norse: handfesta) sealed a marriage agreement; the ceremony was performed before witnesses and the gods</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Bridal ale (Brúðlaup)</strong> — the wedding feast involving sacred mead/ale dedicated to the gods; the couple drank together from a common cup; offerings were made to Frigg (goddess of marriage) and Freyr/Freya (fertility)</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Property transfer</strong> — marriage involved the transfer of a morning-gift (morgengifu) from the husband to the wife after the first night; this was her personal property and a mark of her new status</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Divorce</strong> — permitted in Norse custom; either party could dissolve the marriage before witnesses by stating the grounds; return of dowry and morning-gift were regulated</li>';
echo '</ul>';

echo '<h3>Death and the Afterlife</h3>';
echo '<ul>';
echo '<li><strong>Valhöll (Valhalla)</strong> — the hall of the slain, presided over by Odin; warriors who died honorably in battle were chosen by the Valkyries and brought to Valhalla to feast, fight, and prepare for Ragnarök; this was the most prestigious afterlife but available only to a specific category of the dead (battle-slain warriors)</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Fólkvangr</strong> — Freya\'s field; she claimed half of the battle-slain; those not taken by Odin came to her</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Hel</strong> — the realm presided over by the goddess Hel (half-living, half-dead); the destination of those who died of illness, old age, or other non-battle causes; not a place of punishment in the Christian sense but simply a dim, quiet continuation of existence</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Burial customs</strong> — varied by period and region: inhumation (burial in mounds), cremation (especially for nobles and warriors), ship burial (for the most prominent dead); grave goods accompanied the dead to serve their needs in the afterlife; animals and sometimes human companions were sacrificed at major funerals</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Ancestor veneration</strong> — the dead in burial mounds (haugbúar) were believed to continue existing nearby, capable of influencing the living; offerings were made to the dead ancestors at the mounds; the mound itself was sacred family territory</li>';
echo '</ul>';

echo '<h3>Metempsychosis</h3>';
echo '<p>Norse sources contain some evidence of reincarnation belief, though it is not systematically elaborated. The naming of children after dead ancestors was connected to a belief that the ancestor\'s qualities and luck (hamingja) were transmitted to the new child. Some saga accounts describe characters explicitly as reincarnations of specific ancestors. The concept of the hamingja (a kind of personal luck or spiritual power that could be inherited) suggests a form of spiritual continuity across generations. This is not the universal reincarnation of Hindu thought but a more limited, family-specific form of ancestral return — interestingly similar to the Igbo ilo uwa doctrine.</p>';

// CELTIC/DRUIDIC
echo '<hr style="margin:28px 0;border:none;border-top:2px solid #e5e7eb;">';
echo '<h2 style="color:#276749;">⊕ Celtic / Druidic Religion — Full Doctrinal Treatment</h2>';
echo '<p><strong>Theism:</strong> Polytheistic with animistic elements | <strong>Period:</strong> c. 600 BCE – 400 CE | <strong>Status:</strong> Extinct; revived as Neo-Druidism</p>';

echo '<h3>Faith and Belief</h3>';
echo '<p>Celtic religion is among the most difficult to document — the Druids, who were its primary theological custodians, transmitted all knowledge orally and left no written texts. What we know comes from three sources: Greek and Roman accounts (often hostile and certainly outsider perspectives), archaeological evidence (shrines, votive deposits, iconography), and later Irish and Welsh medieval literature (which preserves mythological traditions but in a Christian literary context). This fundamental problem of sources means that Celtic religion must be approached with significant epistemic humility.</p>';
echo '<p>What the evidence suggests: Celtic religion was intensely this-worldly. The Otherworld (Tír na nÓg, Mag Mell, Emain Ablach) was not a post-mortem destination for the virtuous but a parallel realm coexisting with the physical world, accessible at liminal times and places. The divine was present in nature — in rivers, springs, mountains, trees, and animals. Sacred sites (sanctuaries, groves, watersources) were the meeting points between the human and divine worlds. Ritual was the technology for managing these meetings safely and productively.</p>';

echo '<h3>Druidic Knowledge System</h3>';
echo '<p>The Druids were not simply priests — they were the intellectual class of Celtic society, combining the roles of priest, judge, historian, philosopher, astronomer, and educator. Caesar wrote that a young man studying with the Druids might spend twenty years memorizing the oral tradition. The refusal to commit knowledge to writing was not ignorance but theology: oral transmission was considered superior because it required the active participation of living memory, not the passive preservation of a text. The oral knowledge could not be captured by enemies or distorted by scribal errors; it lived in the minds and voices of the initiated.</p>';
echo '<p>Druidic knowledge reportedly included: natural philosophy (the nature of the world), theology (the nature and relationships of the gods), law (judicial procedure and precedent), history (genealogy and tribal memory), astronomy (the calendar and celestial cycles), and medicine (the properties of plants and the treatment of illness). This breadth made the Druids the most socially essential class in Celtic society — without them, the community\'s relationship with the divine, the dead, and the legal order was unmanageable.</p>';

echo '<h3>Doctrines</h3>';
echo '<ul>';
echo '<li><strong>The Otherworld</strong> — a parallel realm of beauty, abundance, and timelessness; not achieved through death alone but accessible through liminal experiences (ecstasy, near-death, fairy encounter); the dead lived there but so did gods and supernatural beings who occasionally visited the human world</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Sacred nature</strong> — divinity was immanent in the natural world; rivers, springs, mountains, and trees were inhabited by divine presences; the oak tree was especially sacred to the Druids; mistletoe (harvested with a golden sickle from the oak) was the most sacred plant medicine</li>';
echo '<li><strong>The head as seat of the soul</strong> — Celtic peoples preserved the severed heads of enemies as trophies and oracles; the head was understood to contain the person\'s power (soul/spirit) even after death; this is among the most documented and most distinctive features of Celtic religious belief</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Tríbhís Mhòr (the Three Realms)</strong> — Land, Sea, and Sky; the three sacred realms each with its divine inhabitants; Celtic ritual space was oriented to these three realms through prayer and invocation</li>';
echo '</ul>';

echo '<h3>Proselytism and Apostasy</h3>';
echo '<p>Celtic religion did not proselytize — it was the ancestral tradition of Celtic peoples. Romanization and eventually Christianization ended Druidism not through ideological competition but through the physical elimination of the Druids as a class (Roman military campaigns in Gaul and Britain, documented by Tacitus, specifically targeted Druidic sanctuaries) and the conversion of Celtic kings to Christianity. The Druids\' knowledge died with those who held it — a catastrophic loss that cannot be recovered from the fragments that survive.</p>';

echo '<h3>Birth Traditions</h3>';
echo '<ul>';
echo '<li><strong>Divination at birth</strong> — the Druids may have cast horoscopes or read omens at birth to determine the child\'s fate and character; Roman sources attribute prophetic powers to the Druids that included foreknowledge of individuals\' destinies</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Naming</strong> — Celtic names were significant: Vercingetorix means "great warrior king"; Boudicca means "victory"; names encoded identity, aspiration, and tribal connection</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Fosterage</strong> — the Celtic practice of fostering children in other noble households for education and alliance-building; the foster relationship (aite/muime) was in some ways more significant than the biological parent relationship in creating social bonds</li>';
echo '</ul>';

echo '<h3>Marriage Traditions</h3>';
echo '<ul>';
echo '<li><strong>Multiple marriage forms</strong> — Irish law (Brehon law, which preserved pre-Christian practice) recognized multiple forms of marriage with different legal statuses; the highest was the marriage of equals with equal property contribution; lower forms governed concubinage and temporary unions</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Beltane unions</strong> — the Beltane festival (May 1) was associated with fertility and seasonal love; temporary unions made at Beltane were socially recognized in some traditions</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Women\'s property rights</strong> — Celtic women had significant property rights; a woman could inherit, own land, and in some traditions take multiple husbands; Boudicca\'s position as queen of the Iceni demonstrates women\'s capacity for political and military leadership</li>';
echo '</ul>';

echo '<h3>Death and the Afterlife</h3>';
echo '<ul>';
echo '<li><strong>Belief in the Otherworld</strong> — the dead passed to the Otherworld, which was understood as pleasant rather than grim (unlike Mesopotamia\'s Kur or early Greek Hades); Caesar specifically noted that the Celts were not afraid of death because they believed in the soul\'s continuation</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Burial customs</strong> — varied by period and region; Iron Age Celts practiced both inhumation and cremation; high-status burials included weapons, jewelry, food and drink, and wheeled vehicles (chariots); the burial goods suggest belief in a continued existence requiring the same material needs as life</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Head preservation</strong> — the heads of honored dead and defeated enemies were preserved; this was related to beliefs about the soul\'s residence in the head and the preservation of spiritual power</li>';
echo '</ul>';

echo '<h3>Metempsychosis</h3>';
echo '<p>Classical sources (Caesar, Diodorus Siculus, Pomponius Mela) consistently attribute belief in metempsychosis to the Druids, specifically as a source of the Celts\' fearlessness in battle. Caesar wrote: "They wish to inculcate this as one of their leading tenets, that souls do not become extinct, but pass after death from one body to another." Whether this refers to human-to-human transmigration, cross-species transmigration, or rebirth in the Otherworld followed by return to a new human body is debated. Irish mythological texts (the Lebor Gabála Érenn and various shape-shifting narratives) contain episodes where divine beings or heroes take multiple successive human and animal forms over long time periods — consistent with a metempsychosis tradition. The evidence suggests that some form of soul transmigration was a central Druidic doctrine, though its precise nature is irrecoverable.</p>';

